1. d4 Nf6 {Bobby came out with an attack which actually seemed from thin air, in a somewhat symmetrical position, and in the end, he won in a position in which two masters in other room commenting the game thought he was losing}

2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 {5.Qb3 maintains more tension. -- Fischer}
cxd5 

6. Nc3 Bg7 {Fischer  presented  his  case  for  Black's  superiority  in  his  game  with Miroslav Filip at Varna, which went 7 Nf3 0-0 8 0-0 Ne4!, an old idea of
Euwe's.}

7. e3 {In  his  American  Chess  Quarterly  notes  Fischer  criticized  this  as
"somewhat passive" compared with 7 Nh3 0-0 8 Nf4, which rules out ...e5 by  concentrating  on  d5.  White  later  passes  up  the  similar  10  Nf4,  which leads to a lifeless middlegame that Fischer regarded as best.}
O-O

8. Nge2 Nc6 9. O-O b6 

10. b3 {It's hard for either side to introduce an imbalance into this
essentially symmetrical variation. Deadeye equality also ensues afer 10.Nf4 e6 11.b3 Ba6 12.Re1 Rc8 13.Ba3 Re8 14.Rc1 (Stahlberg-Flohr, Kemeri 1937) -- Fischer}
Ba6

11. Ba3 {After White's 11th move I should adjudicate his position as slightly
superior, and at worst completely safe. To turn this into a mating position in eleven more moves is more witchcraft than chess! Quite honestly, I do not see the man who can stop Bobby
at this time. -- K.F. Kirby, South African Chess Quarterly}
Re8 {Nine  out  of  ten  masters,  as  Fischer  might  say,  would  coordinate  their heavy pieces with 11...Qd7 and ...Rfc8. But there is little in the position for either side after, say, 12 Re1 Rfc8 13 Rc1 followed by Nf4 and Bf1.}

12. Qd2 {In  retrospect  12  Re1,  and  then  12...Rc8  13  Rc1,  does  a  better  job  of
discouraging  ...e5.  But  White  would  have  to  be  sure  that  this  move  order
didn't just encourage the break by making ...Nxe5-Nd3 more powerful. For
example, 13...e5 14 dxe5 Nxe5 15 Nxd5 Nxd5 (not 15...Rxc1 16 Nxc1!) 16
Qxd5? Nd3 17 Rxc8 Qxc8 18 Rd1 Qc2.
Inserting 16 Rxc8 Rxc8 doesn't help. White loses after 17 Qxd5? Bxe2
18 Rxe2 Qa6! forks the rook and bishop. He is in a bad pin after 17 Bxd5?
Rd8 (18 Nf4 Nd3!).}
e5 {Fischer gave both his 11th and 12th moves exclamation points in his initial
notes  -  and  gave  White's  next  a  question  mark.  He  explained  that  the potential  knight  outposts  at  e4  and  d3  outweighed  the  isolation  of  the  d-pawn. 
! I was a bit worried about weakening my QP, but felt that the tremendous activity obtained by my minor pieces would permit White no time to exploit it. 12...e6 would probably lead to a draw. -- Fischer
}

13. dxe5 Nxe5 

14. Rfd1 {
"Add another to those melancholy case histories entitled: The
Wrong Rook." -- Fischer ~ "This is very much a case of 'the
wrong rook'. One can understand Byrne's desire to break the
pin on the e2-knight, but this turns out to be less important
than other considerations. Fischer spends a lot of time and
energy analysing the superior 14. Rad1!, but still comes to
the conclusion that Black can keep the advantage." -- John
Nunn

Taking on d5 loses a piece (14 Nxd5 Nxd5 15 Bxd5 Bxe2), so White is
faced with the familiar "Which rook?" dilemma. Byrne's choice is natural,
leaving c1 for the QR. Moreover, if White is going to attack d5 with Nf4 he
needs to get out of the a6-e2 pin first.
In  his  first  notes,  Fischer  said  14  Rad1  would  be  met  by  14...Ne4  15
Nxe4 dxe4 16 Bxe4 Qxd2 17 Rxd2 Nc4 18 Bxa8 Nxd2 19 Rd1 Nc4 20
bxc4 ("best") Rxa8 with a strong endgame for Black.
But Yuri Averbakh embarrassed Fischer by finding 20 Bc6! after which
White wins, e.g. 20...Rc8 21 bxc4 Rxc6 22 Rd8+ or 20...Nxa3  21  Bxe8
Bxe2  22  Rd7!.  This  revelation  was  particularly  painful  since  the  first
articles  Fischer  had  written  for  Chess  Life  were  compilations  of  errors  he
found  in  Soviet  analysis,  responding  to  Russian  allegations  that  he  was
lacking in "self-criticism."
Fischer later wrote that after Averbakh's analysis appeared, he spent an
evening "just staring at the position" with 14 Rad1 until he found a resource
- 14...Qc8 - that would vindicate 12...e5. For instance, 15 Nxd5 Nxd5  16
Bxd5 Rd8 17 f4 Rxd5! 18 Qxd5 Bb7, leads to a winning attack or better
endgame for Black. After the superior 15 Bb2 Qf5 he claimed Black "keeps
the initiative."
Evans,  in  his  syndicated  newspaper  column,  gave  a  slightly  different
version.  After  seeing  Averbakh's  analysis,  Fischer  "brooded  over  this
problem for weeks" before finally coming up with 14...Qc8, he wrote. "After
this Bobby stopped publishing analysis."}
Nd3 {
Now it's all systems go for the Fischer rocket. -- Robert Wade

The threat of 15...Ne4! is potent. For example,
(a) 15 Nd4 Ne4 16 Nxe4 dxe4 17 Bb2 Rc8 and Black's pieces begin to
dominate, or (b)  15  Nf4  Ne4  16  Nxe4!  dxe4!  (16...Bxa1?  17  Nd6)  17  Rb1  Rc8  18
Nxd3  Bc3!  and  ...Bxd3.  Fischer  also  gave  (c),  the  sickly  15  f3  and
concluded 15...Bh6 16 Nf4 d4! or 16 f4 Bg7 and ...Ne4 was excellent for
Black.}

15. Qc2 {There is hardly any other defense to the
threat of ...Ne4. -- Fischer}
Nxf2 {
! The key to Black's previous play. The complete justification for this sac does not become apparent until White resigns! -- Fischer

This would have been unsound if White had developed the right rook at
move 14.}

16. Kxf2 Ng4+ {When he showed off this game a few weeks later at the Marshall Chess
Club, Fischer joked "I'm sure Tal will say I shoulda played rook takes pawn
- but I don't believe it."
After 16...Rxe3 17 Kxe3 Ng4+ 18 Kd2 Rc8 Black has lots of play - but
for a rook and knight he deserves something more concrete. White can even
defend with 19 Nxd5 Rxc2+ 20 Kxc2.}

17. Kg1 Nxe3

18. Qd2 {Byrne: As I sat pondering why
Fischer would choose such a line, because it was so obviously
lost for Black, there suddenly comes...}
Nxg2 {
!! This
dazzling move came as the shocker... the culminating
combination is of such depth that, even at the very moment at
which I resigned, both grandmasters who were commenting on the
play for the spectators in a separate room believed I had a
won game! -- Robert Byrne

This  game  was  played  in  a  separate  room,  away  from  spectators,  who
were  hearing  Nicolas  Rossolimo  describe  18  Nxd1  as  necessary  -  and
18...Nxg2 as incomprehensible.}

19. Kxg2 d4 {! The attacked knight can't move, and 20 Qc2 Rc8 solves nothing.}

20. Nxd4 Bb7+ {The King is at Black's mercy. -- Fischer} 
21. Kf1 {
In a room set aside for commentaries on the games in progress, two grandmasters were stating, for the benefit of the spectators, that Byrne had a won game. Byrne's reply to Fischer's next move must have been jaw dropping! -- Wade

This  looks  artificial  but  it  avoids  the  chief  drawback  to  21  Kg1  -
21...Bxd4+ 22 Qxd4 Re1+ and wins (23 Rxe1 Qxd4+ or 23 Kf2 Qxd4+
24 Rxd4 Rxa1 25 Rd7 Rc8 26 Bb2 Rh1!). Another way of avoiding that
tactic is 21 Kf2. But then 21...Qd7  and  ...Qh3  is  too  much,  e.g.  22  Rac1
Qh3  23  Nf3  Bh6  24  Qd3  Be3+  after  which  25  Qxe3  Rxe3  26  Kxe3
Re8+ 27 Kf2 Qf5 is over.}
Qd7 {
And White resigns. Fischer writes: "A bitter disappointment. I'd hoped for 22.Qf2 Qh3+ 23.Kg1 Re1+!! 24.Rxe1 Bxd4+ with mate ...Qg2 to follow shortly." - key  point,  missed  by  Rossolimo  among  other  high-rated  spectators. In 1998 the British Chess Magazine listed 23...Re1+!! as one of the greatest moves ever played - even though it was never played.}

22 Qf2  Qh3+  23  Kg1  Re1+!!  24  Rxe1  Bxd4+ 0-1
